			<div class="post_box top post-47361 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-applications tag-applications" id="post-47361">
				<div class="headline_area">
					<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/2018/03/21/sony-mobile-let-xperia-owners-delete-the-facebook-app/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent link to Sony Mobile &#8211; Let Xperia owners delete the Facebook app">Sony Mobile &#8211; Let Xperia owners delete the Facebook app</a></h2>
					<p class="headline_meta">by <span class="author vcard"><a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/author/xb/" class="url fn">XB</a></span> on <abbr class="published updated" title="2018-03-21">21st March 2018</abbr></p>
					<p class="headline_meta">in <span><a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/category/applications/" rel="category tag">Applications</a></span></p>
				</div>
				<div class="format_text entry-content">
<p><img src="http://www.xperiablog.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Facebook-Xperia-150x150.png" alt="" width="150" height="150" class="alignright size-thumbnail wp-image-47362" srcset="http://www.xperiablog.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Facebook-Xperia-150x150.png 150w, http://www.xperiablog.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Facebook-Xperia-315x315.png 315w, http://www.xperiablog.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Facebook-Xperia.png 325w" sizes="(max-width: 150px) 100vw, 150px" />#deletefacebook</p>
<p>The huge controversy surrounding Facebook in recent days highlights the importance of our privacy and how user data is collected and used. There is a growing movement looking to delete Facebook across the world. </p>
<p>The issue for Xperia owners is that Sony does not allow its users to delete the app &#8211; you can only allow disable it, which is a half-measure. Plus, some users would still have concerns that even in this situation, Facebook can still track you.  <a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/2018/03/21/sony-mobile-let-xperia-owners-delete-the-facebook-app/#more-47361" class="more-link">[read more&hellip;]</a></p>
<p class="to_comments"><span class="bracket">{</span> <a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/2018/03/21/sony-mobile-let-xperia-owners-delete-the-facebook-app/#comments" rel="nofollow"><span>43</span> comments</a> <span class="bracket">}</span></p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="post_box post-47351 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-xperia-xz-series tag-user-manual tag-xperia-xz2 tag-xperia-xz2-compact" id="post-47351">
				<div class="headline_area">
					<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/2018/03/20/dual-sim-xperia-xz2-and-xz2-compact-have-hybrid-sim-trays/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent link to Dual-SIM Xperia XZ2 and XZ2 Compact have hybrid SIM trays">Dual-SIM Xperia XZ2 and XZ2 Compact have hybrid SIM trays</a></h2>
					<p class="headline_meta">by <span class="author vcard"><a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/author/xb/" class="url fn">XB</a></span> on <abbr class="published updated" title="2018-03-20">20th March 2018</abbr></p>
					<p class="headline_meta">in <span><a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/category/xperia-xz-series/" rel="category tag">Xperia XZ series</a></span></p>
				</div>
				<div class="format_text entry-content">
<p><img src="http://www.xperiablog.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Xperia-XZ2-Hybrid-SIM-Tray_Thumb-200x141.png" alt="" width="200" height="141" class="alignright size-thumbnail wp-image-47356" srcset="http://www.xperiablog.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Xperia-XZ2-Hybrid-SIM-Tray_Thumb-200x141.png 200w, http://www.xperiablog.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Xperia-XZ2-Hybrid-SIM-Tray_Thumb-315x222.png 315w, http://www.xperiablog.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Xperia-XZ2-Hybrid-SIM-Tray_Thumb.png 463w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" />Sony Mobile will use hybrid SIM trays for the dual-SIM variants its latest Xperia XZ2 and Xperia XZ2 Compact flagships. This shouldn’t surprise many, as Sony has not supported a dual SIM + micro SD card configuration for its flagship since the Xperia Z5 series. </p>
<p>Both the Xperia XZ2 Dual and XZ2 Compact Dual will allow you to use either two Nano SIM cards together, OR one Nano SIM card and a microSD memory card. If having dual SIM + SD card working together is important to you, then you should check out the Xperia XA2 Ultra. You can find links for the Xperia XZ2 and XZ2 Compact user guides below.  <a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/2018/03/20/dual-sim-xperia-xz2-and-xz2-compact-have-hybrid-sim-trays/#more-47351" class="more-link">[read more&hellip;]</a></p>
<p class="to_comments"><span class="bracket">{</span> <a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/2018/03/20/dual-sim-xperia-xz2-and-xz2-compact-have-hybrid-sim-trays/#comments" rel="nofollow"><span>26</span> comments</a> <span class="bracket">}</span></p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="post_box post-47345 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-firmware category-xperia-xz-series tag-firmware tag-xperia-xz-premium tag-xperia-xz-premium-dual tag-xperia-xz1-compact" id="post-47345">
				<div class="headline_area">
					<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/2018/03/20/xperia-xz-premium-and-xz1-compact-receive-march-2018-security-patch-47-1-a-12-119/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent link to Xperia XZ Premium and XZ1 Compact receive March 2018 security patch (47.1.A.12.119)">Xperia XZ Premium and XZ1 Compact receive March 2018 security patch (47.1.A.12.119)</a></h2>
					<p class="headline_meta">by <span class="author vcard"><a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/author/xb/" class="url fn">XB</a></span> on <abbr class="published updated" title="2018-03-20">20th March 2018</abbr></p>
					<p class="headline_meta">in <span><a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/category/firmware/" rel="category tag">Firmware</a>, <a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/category/xperia-xz-series/" rel="category tag">Xperia XZ series</a></span></p>
				</div>
				<div class="format_text entry-content">
<p><img src="http://www.xperiablog.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Xperia-XZ1-Compact-180x150.png" alt="" width="180" height="150" class="alignright size-thumbnail wp-image-47346" srcset="http://www.xperiablog.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Xperia-XZ1-Compact-180x150.png 180w, http://www.xperiablog.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Xperia-XZ1-Compact-315x263.png 315w, http://www.xperiablog.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Xperia-XZ1-Compact.png 482w" sizes="(max-width: 180px) 100vw, 180px" />Sony Mobile is now rolling the <a href="https://source.android.com/security/bulletin/2018-03-01" rel="noopener" target="_blank">1 March 2018 Android security patch</a> for the Xperia XZ1 Compact and XZ Premium. The Xperia XZ1 had already received this firmware version (47.1.A.12.119) <a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/2018/03/14/xperia-xz1-update-rolling-with-march-2018-security-patch-47-1-a-12-119/">last week</a>, so today we see its siblings receive the update. </p>
<p>As well as the latest security updates, the new firmware provides a bugfix for the persistent GPS notification in the status bar. If you have downloaded the update, please let us know your impressions below.  <a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/2018/03/20/xperia-xz-premium-and-xz1-compact-receive-march-2018-security-patch-47-1-a-12-119/#more-47345" class="more-link">[read more&hellip;]</a></p>
<p class="to_comments"><span class="bracket">{</span> <a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/2018/03/20/xperia-xz-premium-and-xz1-compact-receive-march-2018-security-patch-47-1-a-12-119/#comments" rel="nofollow"><span>25</span> comments</a> <span class="bracket">}</span></p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="post_box post-47339 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-firmware category-xperia-l-series category-xperia-xa-series tag-firmware tag-xperia-l2 tag-xperia-l2-dual tag-xperia-xa2 tag-xperia-xa2-dual tag-xperia-xa2-ultra tag-xperia-xa2-ultra-dual" id="post-47339">
				<div class="headline_area">
					<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/2018/03/19/xperia-xa2-series-and-l2-receive-new-updates/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent link to Xperia XA2 series and L2 receive new updates">Xperia XA2 series and L2 receive new updates</a></h2>
					<p class="headline_meta">by <span class="author vcard"><a href="http://www.xperiablog.net/author/xb/" class="url fn">XB</a></span> on <abbr class="published updated" title="2018-03-19">19th March 2018</abbr></p>
